[[Image:Stortingsgata 16 Oslo.jpg|thumb|225px|Stortingsgata 16, the building in which the Deutsches Theater was housed]]
'''Deutsches Theater''' was a German-language theater in [[Oslo]], Norway which existed between 1941 and 1944, during the [[German occupation of Norway]].
It was established on 1 January 1941 following an order from [[Josef Terboven]], and the first performance was held on 22 April 1941 in [[Nationaltheatret]]. It later moved to new localities, in Stortingsgata 16.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oslopuls.no/hvaskjer/index.jsp?placeId=1018 |title=Filmteateret (a later tenant of Stortingsgata 16) |accessdate=2008-07-25 |work=Oslopuls |publisher=''[[Aftenposten]]'' |date= }}</ref> Its [[premiere]] performance, the operetta ''[[The Land of Smiles]]'' by [[Franz Lehár]], was held on 7 June the same year. The theatre closed in September 1944 because the resources needed to be channeled elsewhere in the German war machine.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last= |first= |author= |authorlink= |coauthors= |editor=Dahl, Hans Fredrik |encyclopedia=[[Norsk krigsleksikon 1940-45]] |title=Deutsches Theater |url=http://mediabase1.uib.no/krigslex/d/d3.html#deutsches-theater |accessdate=2008-07-16 |edition= |date= |year=1995 |month= |publisher=Cappelen |volume= |location=Oslo |id= |isbn=82-02-14138-9 |doi= |pages= |quote= |editor-link= Hans Fredrik Dahl }}</ref>
==See also== *[[Deutsches Theater (Berlin)|Deutsches Theater]], Berlin
