{{Infobox telescope}}
The '''Kunlun Dark Universe Survey Telescope''', also known as '''KDUST''',<ref name="kdust">{{cite web|url=http://www.laboratoryequipment.com/news/2010/09/major-telescopes-added-highest-observatory|title=Major Telescopes Added to Highest Observatory |date=2010-09-27 |accessdate=2014-01-06|work=laboratoryequipment.com}}</ref> is a planned large survey [[telescope]] to be installed at the Chinese [[Antarctic Kunlun Station]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencepoles.org/article/china-research-programmes-at-kunlun-station|title=China’s research programmes at Kunlun Station|author=Jean de Pomereu|date=2012-11-27 |accessdate=2014-01-06|work=sciencepoles.org}}</ref> located at [[Dome A]] ice plateau in [[Antarctica]] in the second half of the 2010s. It is intended to take advantage of the exceptional observation conditions due to low temperature, clean air quality and low disturbances which reduce background noises for infrared observations.

KDUST is a 2.5 meter infrared optical telescope designed to detect and observe Earth-like planets in the Milky Way using infrared light, but at much higher resolution than the [[Antarctica Schmidt telescopes]] project. KDUST will be perched on a 14.5-meter-tall tower to lift it above the turbulence layer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.cas.cn/Ne/CN/201305/t20130502_101575.shtml|title=China Prepares to Spend Billions on Science and Technology|date=2013-05-02|accessdate=2014-01-06|publisher=[[Chinese Academy of Sciences]]}}</ref> KDUST is scheduled to be installed by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nature.com/news/china-aims-high-from-the-bottom-of-the-world-1.11291 |title=China aims high from the bottom of the world |author=Jane Qiu|date=2012-08-29|accessdate= 2012-08-30|work=[[Nature.com]] |publisher=[[Nature Publishing Group]]}}</ref>

