{{Notability|date=August 2018}}
{{Refimprove|date=August 2018}}
'''Mekkawi Said''' ({{lang-ar| مكاوي سعيد}};&nbsp; 6 July 1956 – 2 December 2017) was an Egyptian novelist and short story writer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.banipal.co.uk/contributors/627/mekkawi-said/|title=Banipal (UK) Magazine of Modern Arab Literature - Contributors - Mekkawi Said|website=www.banipal.co.uk|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContentP/18/282597/Books/Egyptian-author-Mekkawi-Said,--Arabic-Booker-Prize.aspx|title=Egyptian author Mekkawi Said, 2008 Arabic Booker Prize nominee, dies - Books - Ahram Online|website=english.ahram.org.eg|language=en|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref> He studied at [[Cairo University]]. He worked as a scriptwriter and publisher, operating the Al-Dar publishing house in Cairo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.literaturfestival.com/participants/authors/2009/mekkawi-said|title=Mekkawi Said — internationales literaturfestival berlin|website=www.literaturfestival.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>

Said published his first book, a collection of short stories, in 1981. Since then, he has published several more [[short story]] collections and two novels. His second novel ''Cairo Swan Song'' was a bestseller and was nominated for the inaugural [[Arabic Booker Prize]] in 2008. The novel has also been translated into English by [[Adam Talib]] and published by the [[AUC Press]].

Said was a recipient of the Egyptian State Prize for Literature.

